3135 Kifer Road (Bldg 3) Santa Clara

TOPIC:  Intelligent Assistants: Presenting One-to-many Hypertext Links
        Scott Fisher

Hypertext makes it possible to jump from one point in an
electronic document to another easily, quickly, and best
of all reversibly.  Most popular hypertext packages now
support a "Go back" button, effectively transforming any link
into a bidirectional link.  But what about situations where
the link is multidirectional -- not just bidirectional?  How
can you present the user with information about where there may
be many links in the document set, without losing your audience
in the confusion?

Author and columnist Scott Fisher presents a strategy for
delivering easy-to-understand one-to-many hypertext links,
adaptible to any electronic delivery system.  He will show
examples from the forthcoming CD-ROM release of his book
"Multimedia Authoring: Building and Developing Documents"
(AP Professional), and will also demonstrate how to set up
these "intelligent assistants" in a number of popular
electronic authoring systems, including FrameMaker 4.0 and
Macromedia Director.


